Visualizing Uni-variate distributions.
 - Univariate - one variable
Visualiztion techniques for sample uni-variate data
 - strip plots
 - swarm plots
 - violin plots
 - box plots

# Strip plot
 - draws a visualization on number line to show the random single-variable

# Using strip plot

sns.stripplot(y='tip', data=tips)
plt.ylabel('tip($)')
plt.show()

Grouping with  stripplot()
sns.stripplot(x='day', y='tip', data=tip)
plt.ylabe('tip($)')
plt.show()

#disadvantages 
- if there are nearing values, at large, then it plot are drawn on each other making less visible

Spreading out strip plots
- use jitter and size

sns.stripplot(x='day', y='tip', data=tip, size=4, jitter=True)
plt.ylabe('tip($)')
plt.show()

#disadvantages  

# swarm plot
sns.swarmplot(x='day', y='tip', data=tip)
plt.ylabe('tip($)')
plt.show()

when to use when not
- when there are more similar samples
- to group with color e.g. sex of the people (by using argument hue)

sns.swarmplot(x='day', y='tip', data=tip, hue='sex')
plt.ylabe('tip($)')
plt.show()

# changing the orientation using argument 'h'
sns.swarmplot(x='tip', y='day', data=tip, hue='sex', orient='h')
plt.ylabe('tip($)')
plt.show()


# box plots or violin plots
when to use and when not to use
 - they are better than other plots strip and swarm to represent the sampled data
 - box plot are beneficial, to show mean, mediam, quartile, 25%, 50% and 75% and count

Using violinplot()

plt.subplot(1,2,1)
sns.boxplot(x='day', y='tip', data=tips)
plt.ylabe('tip($)')

plt.subplot(2,2,1)
sns.violinplot(x='day', y='tip', data=tips)
plt.ylabe('tip($)')

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# combining plots (violin plot with swarm plot)
sns.violinplot(x='day', y='tip', data=tips, inner='None', color='lightgray')

# - by using argument inner=None to disable inner box 
sns.swarmplot(x='day', y='tip', data=tips, size=4, jitter=True)
plt.ylabe('tip($)')
plt.show()



 
